#text: Shares of Actuant

rose after the diversified industrial manufacturer reported better-than-expected third-quarter results. Although its revenue fell 7.5 percent from the same period in fiscal 2000 to $123.9 million, the company reported earnings of 50 cents a share vs. 95 cents in the year-ago period. The profit for the latest quarter topped the consensus of 43 cents as derived in a First Call/Thomson Financial survey. Actuant also lowered revenue expectations to an estimated range of $116 million to $121 million for the fiscal fourth quarter. The stock rose 5 cents to close at $16.15.

#text: Hosting services company Exodus Communications

warned its revenue for growth for the quarter and the year will be below the company's previous guidance. Revenue is expected to be about $315 million, down compared with the year-ago total of $348.7 million. Revenue for the year will be about $1.35 billion. Analysts polled by First Call had been expecting second-quarter revenue of about $355.31 million and full-year revenue of about $1.54 billion. The company cited a drop in the rate of new customer installations, an increase in the rate of cancellations, reductions of orders from existing customers and an increase in reserves related to "dot com failures." Shares closed down 59 cents to $2.25.
